Unprecedented pressures in several directions at the global oceanic ecosystem are combined and creating a frequency of difficulties for almost all marine creatures, says WWF's "Live Blue Planet" report.
Coral reefs are seriously at risk of decline (WWF) Some marine habitats, such as mangroves and large grass, which depend on many other species, have experienced a significant decline, while the entire population of commercially valued fish, such as macro and tuna, have declined by three quarters compared to the 1970s, the report shows.
Many coral reefs, usually described as tropical forests of the oceans due to their huge biodiversity, could be threatened by extinction up to the middle of this century if the acidity of the ocean continues to deteriorate, as a result of the increased levels of CO2 in the atmosphere, causing a direct proportional increase in the level of carbonic acid in the sea.
"Healthy seas are a source of extraordinary natural beauty and wonder and are also a basis for the functioning of the global economy," said Louise Heaps, head of marine policy adviser to WWF-UK, who contributed to the preparation of the report.
"By overfishing, which damage coastal habitats, and without solving the problem of global warming, we resemble the seeds of an ecological economic disaster," said Dr. Heaps.
The report, based on a review of the published scientific literature, but also on the indexes of the living planet, a database maintained by the Zoological Society of London, is one of the most detailed studies on marine life ever undertaken.
Nearly 20% of the total mangrove areas disappeared between 1980 and 2005 (WWF) It investigated a wide variety of marine species, fish, sea turtles and sea cucumbers - an animal similar to a worm, with rough skin - up to marine plants such as mangroves and algae.
The report found that the algae have decreased by about 30% in the last century, while the total mangrove areas have decreased by 20% between 1980 and 2005, mainly as a result of shrimp and other forms of aquaculture.
During one generation, human activity has caused huge damage to the ocean, catching fish faster than it can reproduce and also destroying their banks.
Deep changes are needed to ensure an abundant oceanic life in the next generations," said Marco Lambertini, general director of WWF International.
Some of the most dramatic declines have occurred in fishing species for commercial profits.
For example, 58 out of 17 species belonging to the Scrombidae family - macro, tuna and sardines - have decreased by 74% between 1970 and 2010, without giving a sign of recovery, says the report.
We are in a fishing race that could end up depriving people of a vital food source and an essential economic engine.
Excess fishing, destruction of marine habitats and climate change have serious consequences for the entire human population, and poor communities, which are based on the sea, will be hit the fastest and most powerful," Lambertini said.
"The collapse of ocean ecosystems could trigger a serious economic decline and could undermine our struggle to eradicate poverty and undernutrition," he continued.
Professor Ken Norris, the scientific director of the ZL, said: “These alarming figures prove how quickly people change plants and animals in the ocean and represent a clear warning about the problems we may face as a result.”
Large grass: deep underwater “passions”, which catch rich sediments in minerals and stabilize the seabed.
Over the last century, the cover area has decreased by 30%.
Mangrove: their existence is known in 123 countries, almost half of the total area representing only five countries.
Almost 20% of all mangrove areas disappeared between 1980 and 2005, mainly due to human invasion.
Coral reefs: some of the richest and most biologically productive habitats on earth.
A quarter of all marine species live in or near coral reefs, but three quarters of them are currently threatened and many may disappear during this century if the acidity of the ocean continues to deteriorate.
Deep habitats: very little is known about the deepest areas of the ocean, but the decline in the amount of fish caught in these inaccessible locations over the last 40 years suggests that they are also affected by global marine changes.
