Antidepressants taken during pregnancy do not affect the child
Three new studies note that the administration of antidepressants in pregnant women has no effect on the neural or behavioral development of their children.
Studies have shown that selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) present an increased risk of postpartum bleeding, but researchers have stated that depression is an even greater risk for women and their children, which is why they should be treated.
“These studies add an increasing set of evidence on the safety of the administration of antidepressants during pregnancy,” said John Thorp, deputy editor-in-chief of the International Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology, who published all three studies.
Although there are some increased risks, so far the evidence seems to show that the risks of untreated depression are higher than those of antidepressants.
The Norwegian Institute for Public Health coordinated a study on the motor development of children treated with SSRI, analyzing data of 51 404 children from the Norwegian Cohort Study of Mother and Child, investigating the effects of using SSRI for the development of motor skill at the age of 3.
Researchers found that 381 mothers had been using SSRI during pregnancy, and 159 of these had been treated with prolonged medication.
Although exposure to SSRI was associated to some extent with a delay in engine development, researchers wrote in the study that the association “was not so significant as to give the delay a clinical significance”.
A group of researchers from the Australian Adelaide University conducted a data review for 49 000 women from the Danish National Birth Cohort to discover the effects of SSRI administration on children's behaviour up to the age of 7.
The study found that untreated depression in pregnant women was associated with an increased risk of behavioural problems.
In 210 children whose mothers had been treated with SSRI depression, there was no increased risk of behavioural problems compared to 231 children who were more prone to behavioural problems such as hyperactivity, lack of attention and socialization problems.
The same group of Australian researchers also found in a separate study that mothers are more likely to bleed after birth if they are treated with SSRI.
Analysis of medical data from 30,198 who were born at a university hospital in Adelaide between 2002 and 2008 showed that the risk of postnatal bleeding increased by 5%, between 11 and 16%, if women were treated with SSRI.
The risk of severe bleeding or postnatal anaemia has doubled, researchers have reported.
Researchers said that, although the study linked the administration of SSRI with increased risk, there are a large number of variables - from the medicines taken during birth to the limited amount of information that researchers had about women's specific medical conditions - that could have had an effect on the potential for bleeding.
“It is possible for women who have taken antidepressants at an advanced pregnancy stage to be those with the most severe stage of the disease, and this is the reason for the increased risk of postnatal bleeding, not antidepressants,” says Dr. Luke Grzeskowiak, professor at Adelaide University.
