The author of these ranks is not at all an admirer of the red flags (and not of those who float them), but respects the democratic political traditions built around them.
If Jeremy Corbyn manages to join the left of yesterday's tomorrow, this love story between him and the Laburist Party base will have part of a happy-end.
I don't think that's gonna happen like this, but it seems to me premature to talk about the great and inevitable electoral defeat, over five years, of a leader chosen the other day.
Now, however, we can refer to procedures: we have witnessed a democratic exercise of an impressive scope.
The British Labour have not invented the voting system directly for the party leader, among the western left.
A more complicated system, based on motions, which allows the expression of all members and supporters, has been in practice for a few years; in addition, they organised a preliminary competition for the appointment of the candidate to the 2012 presidentials.
However, the internal election of workers seems more spectacular and more political, as the new leader elected automatically becomes his peak of launch in future elections.
It is, of course, also a matter of the political system, the customisation of power being more pronounced in the UK than on the other side of the Hand Channel.
In addition, participation in the vote was high in all three "searches": members themselves, members of the unions and other organisations affiliated to the party and, finally, the group of supporters (who received the ballot after a summary registration procedure).
This last group gives us interesting information about the perceptions of left-wing segments of British society, especially those of young or middle-aged people, educated, interested in the political phenomenon.
Many of them will choose to become more involved in the future, precisely because of the signal offered by Corbyn's victory.
There are no, as far as I know, sociological surveys that tell us too much about the attitudes of this laborer "external quest", so the precaution speculation is allowed.
I think we have a lot of attitudes similar to those of the supporters Podemos (Spain) or even SYRIZA (Greece), with the observation that they will travel through the traditional channels of the left.
If we have to identify a "antisystem" vocation, it is primarily reflected by rejecting the centrist line, New Labour (for many, just a dissimulated form of much-thochcherism).
The second component would be the repudiation of the leaders considered guilty by the two successive election failures, one of the arguments being that they did not go left enough, that they were not firmly delimited by the Tony Blair era.
The second feature - after me, and more suggestive - is offered by the recent referendum on independence of Scotland.
If we separate from the separatist message and focus strictly on aspirations for other political issues, we see how Scottish nationalists have captured the energies of social-friendly segments of the public, animated by the aspirations of equity, disarmament and hostile to military involvement over theft, but also sensitive to the new themes of the left: ecology, gender, assistance for poor countries.
Scottish workers have thus lost an electorate to whom they should have, at least in principle, had privileged access, but which they can now recover (see their enthusiasm towards Corbyn's campaign).
Such energies exist everywhere in the United Kingdom, but the old leadership couldn't attract them.
Jeremy Corbyn, with his vocation as an outsider, has more chances of success than Ed Miliband, the laborer's "aristocrat."
The comparison with Scotland tells us more, I think, than the one with the left anti-system from the southern periphery of Europe.
The term "anti-system" is too harsh: "anti-establishment" seems more appropriate to me.
Until next week we'll find out more about Jeremy Corbyn's first step as the leader of the opposition.
We will see if the red flag will not arise in the House of Commons (it would not be for the first time), after the new leader will have occupied his place, first of all, the opposition banks.
However, what Jeremy Corbyn now wants from his colleagues in Parliament is primarily unity - and in this regard he even has reasons to be worried.
